Jan Algermissen wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Question: is there any promise by Amazon about how the HTML of the
&gt; site looks like? No. And for good reason. They do not want clients to
&gt; start making assumptions beyond text/html.
&gt; 

Wait a minute, yes, they do.  HTML is general enough that there are a
variety of ways, RESTful or not, to code a shopping cart in text/html.
We now have the GoodRelations ontology, which allows this diverse
markup to all have the same _meaning_ from one site to the next.

I posted a link last week to my source for the assertion that BestBuy&#39;s
online sales increased by 30% after they used RDFa to implement GR.
Any number of domain-specific vocabularies like GR may be embedded in
any number of ubiquitous media types, to address any problem.  There is
no prohibition against this in REST, in fact, it&#39;s exactly what REST
advocates.

-Eric
